Torrelbenc on Minorca is a beautifulllll hotel. The attention to design detail is stunning, but it’s also super connected to the land. Flora and fauna everywhere; each inhale is a journey… rosemary, basil, eucalyptus. Birds chirping, snails and turtles and lizards visiting… fantastic, healthy food. Just a magical place!

I would not have visited except for going on retreat with @valerieoula and I’m so delighted to be here. If you’re looking to try somewhere new — somewhere CHILL and grounded, consider here! A ~20 plane ride from Barcelona airport. 

🦎🌸🌳

I’d like to tell you what you’re looking at here: a 👏 freaking 👏 generational 👏 milestone.

While my own parents were college educated, they were strictly religious and when I was 14 years old, they voluntarily turned me over into the highly abusive “troubled teen industry.” (Basically a group of for-profit companies that exploit children for insurance / state money and act as a prison pipeline. When I was first locked up I hadn’t even sworn in front of my parents. So.)

I spent three years being locked up against my will in seven different institutions. A week after I turned 17, I was released into a homeless shelter and began financially supporting myself. I wasn’t allowed to finish traditional high school, and my attempts at community college ended with pregnancy. I spent 13 years as a single mother, moving around a ton, building a career, and raising a child on my own — until @joshclark joined forces 12 years ago. I built my life and career without the education or network that comes from college.

And this week, MY AMAZING KID GRADUATED WITH HONORS FROM NYU. 💜🎓💪

She busted her ASS and turned all kinds of closed doors and “no’s” into a path that got her here. Although she was an A student at a great high school, our first round of college applications ended with 15 no’s. (!!) 

She deferred a second choice school, took a gap year, and midway through decided to switch directions and study photography at FIT for two years, before she managed to be one of very few students invited to transfer to NYU. Her tenacity and ability to work through obstacles is amazing.

I feel very much like this is my celebration, too. I took what I wasn’t given and figured out how to give her options that I never had. I f*cking ALCHEMIZED this sh*t. And she took very tough circumstances of her own, and spun her own gold. We WERKED. 

So: yeah, I’m proud as f*cking hell. Of her! And of me. I’m grateful to Josh for a decade plus of love and support of both of us. And I’m ready to celebrate this milestone! I’m brimming with joy for her, and frankly I’m proud as hell of me, too. 🥳

Studio is coming along! A lot left to do, but feeling like she’s looking real cute. 💁🏻‍♀️ Can’t wait to host a few friends & clients here starting this fall.

Free live online class, this Wednesday Jan 17th! 

How can we best show up for our clients beyond subject matter training in yoga / meditation / other healing arts? As healers living amongst the wellness industrial complex, how can we ensure that we are helping people, and not causing harm?

Many trainings and certifications teach us the practices, but may only nod at important subjects like how to hold space for people in crisis, how to teach the practices without our egos getting in the way, and how to work with special populations. 

Holy Shift founder Liza Kindred takes us on a gentle exploration of the foundations of wellness teaching: being a spiritual friend first, holding the seat of the student, awareness of power dynamics, staying authentic (like, for real), and more. It’s possible to gain confidence by using a framework for how to best show up for clients–and ourselves.

Free for all, members and non-members alike! We'd love to have you join us.

Link in bio, or at HolyShift.co 🥳
